    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-23T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-23T15:00:00-05:00" n="902"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d902">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867.248 Martin Co., Glenn L./19: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-23T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 23, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>11. Your No. 5, February 21, noon. It is not the policy of this Government to
                    encourage the export trade in arms and munitions of war. See circular
                    instruction of December 7, 1932.<note n="30" xml:id="d902fn30">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Decisions in regard to the manufacture of military equipment manufactured
                    according to specifications under the control of the War Department is a matter
                    within the exclusive jurisdiction of the Secretary of War. I cannot with
                    propriety volunteer advice to the Secretary of War in such a matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
